# Project: Email Template Editor (Postmark-like for AWS SES)

## Purpose
A web-based email template management tool that supports:
- Writing HTML/CSS email templates with Handlebars syntax (`{{variable}}`)
- Live preview with mock data injection
- Template management (CRUD)
- All data persisted in **IndexedDB** (no backend required)

## Tech Stack
- **Framework**: React 18 + TypeScript (strict mode)
- **Build tool**: Vite
- **Styling**: Tailwind CSS (utility-first, no custom CSS unless necessary)
- **State management**: Zustand
- **IndexedDB**: `idb` library (wrapper around IndexedDB)
- **Handlebars rendering**: `handlebars` npm package
- **Code editor**: `@uiw/react-codemirror` with HTML mode
- **Package manager**: pnpm

## Architecture
```
src/
  components/       # Reusable UI components
    editor/         # Code editor panel (HTML + Text tabs)
    preview/        # Preview panel (renders compiled template)
    mockdata/       # Mock data JSON editor panel
    templates/      # Template list, create, delete
  hooks/            # Custom React hooks (useTemplates, useMockData, usePreview)
  stores/           # Zustand stores
    templateStore.ts
    editorStore.ts
  lib/
    db.ts           # All IndexedDB logic via `idb`
    handlebars.ts   # Template compilation helpers
  types/
    index.ts        # Shared TypeScript interfaces
  pages/
    index.tsx       # Main editor page
```

## Core Data Models
```typescript
interface Template {
  id: string;           // uuid
  name: string;
  alias: string;        // slug, unique
  subject: string;      // supports {{variables}}
  htmlBody: string;
  textBody: string;
  mockData: Record<string, unknown>; // JSON for preview
  createdAt: number;
  updatedAt: number;
}
```

## Coding Standards
- TypeScript strict mode — never use `any`, use `unknown` and narrow types
- Named exports only — no default exports except for pages
- All async functions must use `try/catch` with proper error handling
- Use `const` over `let` wherever possible
- Functional components only — no class components
- Custom hooks for all business logic — keep components as dumb as possible
- Avoid prop drilling — use Zustand store for shared state
